	<fdd:identificationAndDescription>
		<fdd:fullName>MXF Operational Pattern 1a (OP1a)</fdd:fullName>
		<fdd:keywords>
			<fdd:keyword>wrapper formats</fdd:keyword>
			<fdd:keyword>container formats</fdd:keyword>
		</fdd:keywords>
		<fdd:description>
			<p>Operational Pattern (OP) for a file with a single playable essence comprising a single essence element or interleaved essence elements, i.e., the content may consist of multiple, interleaved tracks of picture and sound.  According to an Avid <a href="http://www.avid.com/static/resources/common/documents/mxf.pdf">promotional booklet</a>, OP1a files are &quot;nicely self-contained and can work well in applications where each file represents a complete program or take . . . [but] may be less applicable to content authoring steps such as non-linear editing, where programs are created by slicing and dicing different sections of source material.&quot;  The latter application is better served by <fddLink id="fdd000265">MXF_OP-Atom</fddLink>.</p>
		</fdd:description>
		<fdd:shortDescription>Operational pattern for a file with a single playable essence comprising a single essence element or interleaved essence elements, i.e., the content may consist of multiple, interleaved tracks of picture and sound.</fdd:shortDescription>
